getSON <- function(index){
  index=index[which(index[,3]!=-999.9),]
  tmp=index[which((index[,2]==9)|(index[,2]==10)|(index[,2]==11)),]
  l=length(unique(tmp[,1]))-1
  out=rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    out[i]=mean(tmp[which(tmp[,1]==unique(tmp[,1])[i]),3])
  }
  out1 <- cbind(unique(tmp[,1])[2:(l+1)],out)
  return(out1)
}

library(glmnet)
xminus <- seas_HDD[1:60,2]
xplus <- seas_HDD[2:61,2]
r1 <- sum((xminus-mean(xminus))*(xplus-mean(xplus)))/((sqrt(sum((xminus-mean(xminus))^2)))*(sqrt(sum((xminus-mean(xminus))^2))))
n1 <- n*(1-r1)/(1+r1)
expon <- 2/3*(1-n1/n) ###Now the Wilks 5.36 becomes L=(101-L)^(expon)
fL <- function(L,expon){
  n=100
  result <- L-(n-L+1)^expon
  return(result)
}
##Check the approximate location of root of fL##
L=seq(-100,100,0.1)
eps=1e-7
max=max(L)
min=min(L)
tmp=0.5*(max+min)
check <- fL(tmp,expon)
while(abs(check)>eps){
  if(check<0){
    min=tmp
    tmp=0.5*(max+min)
  }else{
    max=tmp
    tmp=0.5*(max+min)
  }    
  check <- fL(tmp,expon)
}
L <- round(tmp) 
###moving window cross validation with overlap###
nblock <- floor(61/L)
lambda=seq(0,5,by=0.01)
MSE=array(0,dim=c(length(lambda),nblock))
meanMSE=rep(0,length(lambda))
for(i in 1:length(lambda)){
  for(j in 1:nblock){
    if(j==1){
      xtest=pdSON[1:L,]
      xtrain=pdSON[(L+1):61,]
    }else if(j>1){
      xtest=pdSON[((j-1)*L+1):(j*L),]
      xtrain=rbind(pdSON[1:((j-1)*L),],pdSON[(j*L+1):61,])
    }
    ridge_mod = glmnet(as.matrix(xtrain[,2:11]), xtrain[,1], alpha=0, lambda = lambda[i], nlambda=1)
    ridge_pred = predict(ridge_mod, newx = as.matrix(xtest[,2:11]))
    MSE[i,j]=sqrt(mean((ridge_pred - xtest[,1])^2))
  }
  meanMSE[i]=mean(MSE[i,])
}
lam=lambda[which(meanMSE==min(meanMSE))]
print(paste0("lambda=",lam))

c

plot(x=lambda,y=meanMSE,type='l',col="green",ylab="standard error of prediction",lwd=2)

When lambda is small, the variance of the parameter is ignored when considering a cost function in regression, and the performance of the prediction is not good enough because of the possible large variance of the parameters, which making the model is better at fitting training data than predicting new data. When lambda is large, the variance of the parameter is better controled, however, the fit to the original training dataset has relative smaller weight, under this condition, the model tends to capture less of the information from the training data, and making the prediction less accurate. Only when the balance between model parameter variance and the fit to the training data is obtained, the model can perform an overall best prediction to the new datas. The beta can only approaching zero, so the standard error of prediction will keep changing.

Answer to c in LASSO regression: When lambda is small, the variance of the parameter is ignored when considering a cost function in regression, and the performance of the prediction is not good enough because of the possible large variance of the parameters, which making the model is better at fitting training data than predicting new data. When lambda is large, the variance of the parameter is better controled, however, the fit to the original training dataset has relative smaller weight, under this condition, the model tends to capture less of the information from the training data, and making the prediction less accurate. Only when the balance between model parameter variance and the fit to the training data is obtained, the model can perform an overall best prediction to the new datas. When lambda is very large, the beta can be zero, then the corresponding predictor can be negligible, and when all of the beta becomes zero, the models standard error of prediction becomes the standard error of prediction when all of the predicted value becomes the interception.

rmannual=array(0,dim=dim)
for(i in 1:dim[1]){
  for(j in 1:dim[2]){
    yr=rep(1871:2012,each=12)
    mon=rep(c(1:12),2012-1871+1)
    time=cbind(yr,mon)
    prestmp=pres[i,j,]
    preswd=cbind(time,prestmp)
    presclim=rep(0,12)
    for(k in 1:12){
      presclim[k]=mean(preswd[which(preswd[,2]==k),3])
    }
    presclimnew=rep(presclim,2012-1871+1)
    presnew=prestmp-presclimnew
    rmannual[i,j,]=presnew  ##Here I removed annual cycle
  }
}

  mat <- array(0,dim=c(dim[1],dim[2]))
  for(i in 1:dim[1]){
    for(j in 1:dim[2]){

After latitude scaling, the spatial patterns of the first two eigenvectors remain similar, while the signs of the spatial patterns of the other eigenvectors (3rd, 4th and 5th) are opposite to that before latitude scaling. This change in sign but mirrored pattern of the 3rd-5th eigenvector might indicating that although the signs changed, the spatial structure revealed by the eigenvectors remains the same. The first eigenvector map shows similar pattern to Pacific/North American Pattern. It is important to note that the PNA has been found to be strongly influenced by the El Nio-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) phenomenon. The positive phase of the PNA pattern tends to be associated with Pacific warm episodes (El Nio), and the negative phase tends to be associated with Pacific cold episodes (La Nia). The second eigenvector map shows similar pattern to no El Nio year in northern America. And the comparison between the positive phase of the PC1TS and the negative phase (El Nio) of the PC2TS tends to be consistent, possibly indicating a negative correlation between PNA and El Nio. The other three/four eigenvectors do not contribute too much variables, and the patterns are not obvious enough to extract useful informations about their physical meaning.
